The break-even price refers to the price at which the net present value of the company or the project becomes equal to zero. This means that all assets and liabilities are equal. 

The current cash flow of the company can be used to solve this problem. The current cash flow can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Cash flow}&=\dfrac{(\text{New policy quantity}-\text{Old policy quantity)}\times(\text{P*}-\text{Price of old policy})}{\text{Required rate of return}}
\end{aligned}$$

Where $P^*$ is the break-even price.
